                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">The objectives above are questions and half-solutions in current research in discrete geometry. For instance, for (2), I and Matousek proved recently (the paper is accepted in Discrete Comp Geometry) that for any two measures in the plane there is a four-fan (i.e. a point and four half-lines starting at the point) such that one sector has measure 2/5, and the other three have measure 1/5 in both measures. Several questions are to be answered yet in this direction, the most exciting is probably the existence of an equipartition by a four-fan. For (3), there has been progress in understanding that the fractional Helly number is a central concept connected to many others in combinatorial convexity. The fractional Helly number of the convexity space of lattice points leads to the following question. Assume K is a family of convex sets in R^d with the property, that any d+1 among them have a common point in Z^d, the integer lattice. Does this imply the existence of a set FcZ^d whose size depends only on d, such that F^ K = 0 for every K E K!</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
